<TEXT>
the writer who reported from afghanistan in june 
1980 six months after the soviet intervention recently spent five 
weeks there to assess changes after the soviet pullout nine years 
later 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
some of the hatred heaped on the soviet 
union during its nineyear military intervention has shifted to the 
united states the chief supplier of the guerrilla rockets that kill 
far more civilians than soldiers 
six months after the soviet withdrawal many afghans sought out a 
visitng american journalist to accuse the united states of financing 
death not promoting peace 
i hate the american government because they are assisting the 
opposition groups in our country theyre killing our people we 
want peace to come to afghanistan said 22yearold takar 
he lost three relatives in the failed guerrilla assault on the 
southeastern city of jalalabad that began after the last soviet 
troops withdrew on feb 15 
public hostility to the soviets was so strong after their troops 
poured into the country in december 1979 that few soldiers or their 
families ventured out into downtown bazaars and restaurants 
when soviets passed by afghans shouted insults sometimes 
accompanied by a shove pinch or handful of tossed pebbles in 
contrast for american visitors afghans reserved smiles and pleas 
for the united states to supply antitank and antiaircraft weapons 
to moslem guerrillas 
soviets remain unloved and still keep a low profile but they are 
no longer the enemy interloper the soviet embassy compound remains 
a favorite guerrilla rocket target even though the rebels seem to 
keep missing it and some afghans blame the soviets as well as the 
americans for prolonging the fighting 
all people think the soviet union and the united states want 
war in our country they dont want peace in our country said 
dr mohammad nasser a doctor in kabul we dont want any more 
revolution we just want afghanistan for the afghans 
in the dusty bazaars and crowded tea houses of kabul where nine 
years ago afghans spoke of fighting soviet troops the conversation 
now centers on fear of rockets leaving the city high food prices 
and prospects of a political settlement which inevitably brings up 
the united states 
the united states is now viewed by many afghans as the key player 
in the war ussupplied rockets are terrorizing kabul 
the usbacked guerrillas have failed to topple the government 
of president najib as western diplomats had predicted and as many 
afghans had expected and the rebels internal feuding had turned to 
warfare 
the united states closed its embassy in kabul before soviet 
troops left citing security concerns and there are only a handful 
of americans in kabul fulltime all missionary health workers 
for some afghans the opportunity to confront an american visitor 
was not to be missed 
several times an american journalist was surrounded by crowds of 
20 to 30 afghans many shouting that president bush should stop 
giving weapons to the guerilla mujahedeen or islamic holy warriors 
a few afghans out of earshot of their fellow countrymen backed 
the americans but said washington wasnt doing enough to get rid of 
najib 
nine years ago kabulis complained there was nothing to do in the 
capital and there is even less choice now the only discotheque at 
the continental hotel has closed and so have most restaurants 
curfew is now an hour earlier at 10 pm 
by day kabul is a noisy oriental bazaar where men in turbans sip 
tea and haggle over japanese cameras russian watches and sides of 
lamb 
by night the incoming rockets outgoing soviet scud missiles and 
shots fired by sentries shatter dreams 
the rebels communicate clandestinely as they did nine years ago 
through night letters circulated after curfew one of the 
singlepage letters in early august urged kabul residents to leave 
the city for two weeks to avoid heavy rocketing 
afghans have traditionally fought any foreign interloper and the 
soviets were no exception they were nonbelieving communists who 
threatened the traditional moslem way of life 
najib has gone to great lengths to rebuild mosques destroyed by 
his communist predecessors to precede all his speeches with prayers 
by a mullah and to be photographed praying toward mecca 
with the soviets gone and najib espousing islam some guerrillas 
have made peace with the government saying their fight against the 
infidels has been won but many afghans still grumble 
afghan troops have replaced their soviet counterparts on the 
streets of kabul and other major cities qargah lake outside kabul 
a favorite soviet swimming hole is now a fish farm 
but the afghan government is more dependent than ever on moscow 
for food fuel weapons and ammunition the soviet airlift continues 
with 30 to 200 flights a day according to diplomatic sources and 
hundreds of trucks rumble down the salang highway from the soviet 
border to kabul 
</TEXT>
