police said today that they seized the 88 pounds of 
uranium that was offered for sale to the us embassy in a case that 
has already netted seven arrests 
the uranium was seized sunday at a food dealers house in in 
kurume fukuoka prefecture 560 miles southwest of the capital 
it was contained in 41 glass bottles in six xray prevention 
bags said an official of the tokyo metropolitan police department 
who spoke anonymously 
the official said police experts on chemical materials analyzed 
the substance discovered and found it was natural uranium 
on sept 1 police arrested five people on charges of illegal 
possession of nuclear substances after they took a capsule 
containing about 35 ounces of uranium to the us embassy in early 
august and proposed to sell another 88 pounds of the same substance 
for 83 million 
two more people were arrested on tuesday and friday and an eighth 
person mitsuteru tomoda a 51yearold antique art dealer was put 
on a wanted list 
another police official also requesting anonymity said the food 
dealer told investigators tomoda had asked him to keep the uranium 
the first official said the food dealer whose name was not 
disclosed reported the uranium case to local police after 
consulting with a lawyer 
he identified the arrested groups leader as toshiko nishijima a 
43yearold woman who owns several small companies 
uranium a radioactive element can be used in concentrated forms 
to make nuclear weapons and run nuclear power plants 
police have said analysis of the uranium seized earlier showed it 
was refined natural uranium of 707 percent purity 
the science and technology agencys analysis said only 07 
percent of the uranium was uranium235 the element used for power 
generation and for bombs while the rest was uranium238 
nuclear experts said nuclear power generation needs uranium 
containing more than 3 percent uranium235 and an atomic bomb 
requires uranium that contains more than 90 percent uranium235 
police still were investigating the source of the groups uranium 
and why the group tried to sell it to the us embassy at more than 
2000 times its market value of 275 an ounce 
in japan the handling of uranium is strictly regulated by law 
