a news conference those who have incomes in the millions can well 
afford the modest top tax rates under todays tax system 
dorgans limited capitalgains reduction would be financed by 
raising from 28 percent to 33 percent the maximum tax rate that 
applies to all types of income earned by wealthier taxpayers 
the ways and means committee will resume consideration tuesday of 
a plan endorsed by president bush that would allow investors to 
avoid tax on 30 percent of capital gains which are profits from the 
sale of stock and other assets congressional staff experts estimate 
that 80 percent of the benefit of such a reduction would go to those 
with annual incomes above 100000 
that proposal sponsored chiefly by reps ed jenkins dga and 
bill archer rtexas apparently has the support of a bare majority 
of the ways and means committee 
dorgan said he would prefer no change in taxation of capital 
gains which now are taxed at the same rates as other income he is 
offering the alternative he said only because it appears the 
committee will approve a capitalgains cut 
under dorgans proposal 
thirty percent of capital gains would be excluded from taxation 
for couples with total income of 100000 or less 
the portion of the gain that would be excluded from taxation 
would decline gradually as income rises between 100000 and 
200000 at 150000 income the exclusion would be 15 percent 
no exclusion would be allowed once total income exceeds 200000 
a year 
a quirk in the 1986 tax law that has some people paying a lower 
rate as income rises would be eliminated for example a couple with 
two children and taxable income of 300000 now paying a 28 percent 
rate on all above 201500 would have to pay 33 percent on all above 
that level 
that rate change would affect only the wealthiest 1 percent of 
taxpayers dorgan said 
 
