pilot error and bad weather caused a 
philippine airlines plane to overshoot the runway and slam into a 
busy highway last july killing eight people according to a report 
released monday 
about 90 people were injured when the twinengine bac 111 jet 
plowed through a concrete wall slammed into four vehicles along 
manilas south expressway and came to rest on railway tracks all 
the dead were in cars on the highway 
the governments air transportation office released a 13page 
report on the july 21 accident after completing six weeks of 
investigation 
the probable cause of the accident was that the pilot exhibited 
poor judgment during landing and that the weather was a contributory 
factor said the office chairman oscar alejandro who read the 
findings to reporters 
analyses of the flight recorders showed the pilot twice told 
tower controllers he could not see the runway because of heavy rains 
as he made his approach after a flight from zamboanga city 540 
miles to the south alejandro said 
when the airplane was 150 feet above the runway tower 
controllers saw the plane and told the pilot to accelerate 
alejandro said 
it was at this point that the air traffic controllers told the 
pilot to make a misapproach in other words to go around and try 
for another landing alejandro said instead the pilot decided 
to land 
alejandro said that under philippine law testimony in the report 
cannot be used against the pilot capt ricardo misa in any civil 
suits 
our investigation is not punitive we just want to know what 
happened so we can correct them so that it does not happen again 
alejandro said 
the report recommended that approach and landing lights be 
repaired both at manila and the international airport in cebu city 
alejandro said there were conflicting reports if the lights were 
actually on during the accident 
