a secret directive signed by president bush 
dealing with us military involvement in the war on drugs does not 
envision using us forces in any combat role in latin america the 
white house said today 
a member of the senate intelligence committee however said the 
military will provide protection to us drug enforcement agents and 
other law enforcement officials operating in such nations as bolivia 
and peru 
at the white house spokesman marlin fitzwater confirmed bush 
recently signed a directive outlining the goals and limits of 
military involvement in the war on drugs but he said it does not 
authorize the use of us troops in combat 
sen dennis deconcini dariz said the directive authorizes the 
military to be physically involved with units in the field where 
we have been invited to have our law enforcement people 
he said such protection is designed to prevent incidents similar 
to the torture and murder of us drug agent enrique camarena in 
guadalajara mexico in febuary 1985 
we cant afford another camarena said deconcini a member of 
the intelligence committee 
