<TEXT>
net deposit withdrawals at the nations thrift 
institutions fell to a ninemonth low of 183 million in july the 
government said monday 
the outflow was the smallest since october and followed a 46 
billion withdrawal in june 
the office of thrift supervision attributed the decreased outflow 
to competitive deposit rates and growing public assurance following 
passage earlier in the summer of the new savings and loan law which 
includes 50 billion for the industry over the next 26 months 
the moderation in deposit outflows reflected a further 
narrowing in the spread between deposit rates offered by thrifts and 
their nondepository competition as well as less concern about 
thrifts following enactment of firrea financial institutions 
reform recovery and enforcement act said james barth ots chief 
economist 
until passage of the new law the ots was the federal home loan 
bank board 
the ots had attributed the june outflow to intentional shrinkage 
as thrifts prepared to meet the new laws tough new capital rule 
roughly one in four of the nations 2933 sampls do not meet the 
new standard 150 in tangible capital for every 100 in lending 
which becomes effective in three months the only way thrifts that 
cannot attract new capital can comply is to sell off assets such as 
loans and pay off liabilities such as deposits 
barth said sampls in july reduced their assets by 7 billion a 
monthly total exceeded only by 76 billion in june and 8 billion 
in january 
most of the july reduction was accounted for by a record 74 
billion in mortgage holdings including 7 billion in mortgage pool 
securities one of the most easily sold assets in a thrift portfolio 
for the first seven months of the year a net 398 billion have 
flowed out of thrift accounts compared with an inflow of 115 
billion in the first seven months of 1988 
