<TEXT>
liberal economists monday attacked a plan 
supported by president bush to slash taxes on capital gains 
describing it as a shell game to benefit the wealthy 
this may well be the worst tax idea in the history of the 
republic harvard university economist lawrence summers said at a 
news conference at which he and other analysts said there was no 
evidence a capitalgains cut would stimulate economic growth 
this measure does precisely nothing to encourage savings 
said henry aaron an economist with the brookings institution 
as the house ways and means committee nears a vote on the 
proposed reduction this week panel member rep byron l dorgan 
dnd offered an alternative that would deny any benefit to those 
with annual incomes over 200000 
dorgans bill also would raise the maximum tax rate that applies 
to income of all kind earned by the wealthiest 1 percent 
eliminating a quirk in the 1986 tax overhaul under which the tax 
rate on some wealthy people drops from 33 percent to 28 percent as 
income rises 
there was no evidence that the bushbacked proposal was losing 
support in the committee by unofficial count 19 of the 37 
committee members enough to deliver a onevote victory favor a 
temporary capitalgains reduction proposed by reps ed jenkins 
dga and bill archer rtexas 
it appears the jenkinsarcher plan will win committee approval 
unless chairman dan rostenkowski dill can persuade one of six 
democrats favoring it to support a substitute he has drafted 
the issue has become the biggest tax question facing congress 
since the landmark overhaul of the income tax was enacted in 1986 
it was that law that took away the preferential treatment long 
accorded capital gains profits from the sale of stock and other 
assets 
capital gains are taxed at the same rate as wages and other 
income during the campaign last year bush called for a lower rate 
for capital gains to encourage saving investment and job creation 
he claimed that cutting the capitalgains tax would so stimulate 
the economy that revenue collections would increase years into the 
future thus helping reduce the deficit 
democrats dispute that claim but many expect a capitalgains cut 
to produce a oneyear burst of revenues which would make it easier 
to meet the 1990 deficitreduction target 
unable to find support for his plan bush endorsed the version 
offered by jenkins and archer it would cut the maximum 
capitalgains rate from 33 percent to 196 percent for 2 years the 
rate then would be raised to 28 percent and the system indexed so 
that gains attributed solely to inflation would not be taxed 
economists appearing at a news conference sponsored by reps 
donald pease dohio and sander levin dmich called the proposed 
reduction at best a budgetary quick fix with harmful longterm 
consequences 
it is at worst yet another shell game which will redistribute 
the nations wealth toward those already most well off according 
to a letter signed by aaron and summers 
the letter also was signed by joseph minarik executive director 
of congress joint economic committee alan auerbach chairman of 
the economics department at the university of pennsylvania and 
alan blinder head of the economics department at priceton 
university 
congress joint committee on taxation estimates that 80 percent 
of the benefits of the jenkinsarcher reduction would go to those 
with incomes over 100000 a year 
dorgan who opposes a cut offered an alternative to reduce 
benefits to those with incomes above 100000 a year and eliminate 
them for anybody making over 200000 
if we are going to offer a capitalgains exclusion we should 
offer it to those who need it he said 
