<TEXT>
the national education association unveiled 
teaching guidelines monday to help the nations children appreciate 
the plight of the 3 million homeless families forced to live out of 
cars and in parks 
housing and homelessness a teaching guide is geared to 
grades 4 through 12 with the goals of teaching children about 
homelessness and the need for affordable housing and changing 
negative attitudes toward homeless people 
field trips to homeless shelters are encouraged in the guide as 
well as classroom discussions about substandard and overcrowded 
housing and income levels of groups in a community 
teachers are asked to involve younger students in role playing by 
giving them monopoly money and then asking them to stretch the 
meager wage to cover utilities gasoline and rent 
if this curriculum is well understood by the teacher and taught 
in an open questioning environment it can afford the student the 
opportunity to be educated and to act said carol fennelly 
coauthor of the publication 
as with most americans and as with most social issues the 
problems of poverty and housing are further burdened by a wide 
variety of myths such as people can make it if they want to or 
there is enough housing for everyone if they just work hard enough 
and save 
fennelly said the most positive means of dispelling myths is 
with a clear and simple presentation of reality 
neas new president keith geiger estimated that more than half 
a million children are homeless including as many as 15000 in the 
nations capital alone an estimated 10 million live in substandard 
housing and millions more live in cramped quarters 
the curriculum was produced by housing now a national coalition 
of homelesss and housing groups with assistance from educators 
geiger said neas 1 million members are being encouraged to use 
the curriculum which has been distributed to state affiliates and 
200 of the groups largest local affiliates 
