<TEXT>
norways lapps won a 100year struggle for 
limited selfrule but few of these arctic reindeer herders used 
their chance to vote on monday for lapplands first national 
assembly 
in a 1987 law norway granted this oncenomadic people the right 
to elect an assembly to represent their minority interests but with 
no mandate to enact legislation 
the sami have finally won political rights as a people it has 
all happened so fast i wouldnt have believed it possible even a 
few years ago said hans guttorm a sami candidate the lapps 
prefer to be called sami 
but of the estimated 24000 lapps eligible in norway less than 
5500 registered to vote in the election for an assembly held in 
conjuction with national elections in which they also vote 
those who did marched to the polls under their own flag in 
brightly colored woven costumes trimmed with reindeer leather 
the lapps were electing 39 representatives to the assembly 
called the sameting it will convene oct 9 in karasjok in the 
northern finnmark province 
analysts said the low turnout showed that many lapps 
traditionally hunters fishermen and herdsmen have lost their roots 
there is a certain skepticism especially among older sami 
said peder andersen 72 a pioneer lapp activist told the news 
agency ntb he said the assembly needs time to prove itself 
the sameting wont fix everything that was wrong my hope is 
that it just makes things a little better for the new generation 
the lapps are scattered through the scandinavian and soviet 
arctic their ancient culture was nearly destroyed by active 
policies of assimilation about twothirds of all sami live in 
norway the foreign ministry says 
until the 1950s lappish a language related to finnish was 
forbidden in schools churches and government many sami stopped 
speaking it to their children 
lapps once had to assume norwegian names if they wanted to own 
property sami culture was severely represeed 
an 1890s education document said the sami have no other route 
to a higher level of culture than through the norwegian language and 
culture 
norwegianization was successful an 1888 census showed that 88 
percent of the residents of kvaenangen in northern norway called 
themselves lapps by 1950 none admitted being sami there were no 
mass migrations or major epidemics during the 62 years 
a sami consciousness movement began growing in the 1950s pride 
of their ethnic heritage spread to the scandinavian peoples who 
governed them 
norway now encourages sami culture this autumn the countrys 
first sami university opened sami cultural artistic and media 
institutions have also been formed with government support 
on monday with the assembly vote some lapps said they finally 
felt like equals to norwegians 
mainstream national parties put up candidates for the sameting 
but the sami national union was projected to win a clear majority 
ballots must be collected from isolated villages delaying the 
count results were not expected until wednesday 
election platforms mainly concerned ways to used the new powers 
to influence norways parliament and local governments on sami 
issues 
we sami are one people and national boundaries will not break 
our peoples union we have our own history our own culture and our 
own language which we intend to pass to coming generations 
declared one election platform 
</TEXT>
