the bush administration has decided to hold 
refugee admissions to the united states to 125000 in the next 
fiscal year an increase of slightly less than 8 percent from this 
year a congressional source said monday night 
the figure would include slots for 50000 from the soviet union 
no change from this years allocation the current soviet figure is 
almost double what it was during the start of the current fiscal 
year last oct 1 
but the administration with congressional support in both 
parties has decided it cannot handle any more refugees from the 
soviet union according to several recent reports and the source 
israel has also expressed concern that jewish refugees from the 
soviet union were increasingly choosing to head for the united 
states once out of their homeland depriving the jewish state of 
needed settlers 
the congressional source affiliated with the immigration 
subcommittee of the senate judiciary committee said the issue is 
not the numbers but the backlog he estimated there are 20000 
soviet emigres in rome and vienna awaiting us decisions on their 
eligibility to enter the united states 
under a revision of regulations ordered last year by attorney 
general ed meese each person applying must prove individual 
eligibility for refugee status which means government aid in 
resettlement and admission outside the normal immigration rules 
previously jews from the soviet union were automatically considered 
refugees 
the new decision has made the backlog grow faster than it can be 
processed 
