<TEXT>
the beat of western disco music and 
the flashes from multicolored strobe lights reflect uneasily off 
the dim cobblestone streets and decaying turnofthecentury 
buildings of weimar 
hundreds of people join the dance at the communist youth leagues 
meeting hall on a square named after weimars most illustrious son 
johann wolfgang von goethe 
the rest of the city is quiet its peeling apartment blocks dark 
and its uneven streets deserted 
for decades this oncehistoric city has been neglected by east 
german authorities who have diverted most resources into rebuilding 
east berlin from the rubble of nazi germany that attempt to match 
the opulence of western europe and west germany may have succeeded 
but it has left deep resentment in the provinces of the country 
we are a little town and theres not much left over because the 
bigger cities have priority a young east german woman tells a 
western visitor a popular saying in the country is much harsher 
what the war didnt destroy socialism finished off 
the fortunes of this city have swung from one extreme to another 
since it was the center of german cultural life 
throughout the 18th and 19th centuries weimars enlightened 
royal court attracted the brightest talents in art literature 
philosophy and music johann sebastian bach lived in weimar from 
1708 to 1717 as the court organist and conductor 
later germanys other literary giant of the classicial period 
friedrich von schiller joined goethe and other humanist 
philosophers at the elegant saxon and weimar court 
weimar rose to prominence again in 1919 when after the fall of 
the monarchy the national assembly met here to adopt the weimar 
constitution the document was the framework for a democratic 
republic that would last only until 1933 when adolf hitler came to 
power 
now weimar has come again to resemble what an english 
philosopher said of it in the last century weimar wrote gh lewes 
in 1854 is a very queer little place where the streets are so 
dim that theatergoers take a servant with them to carry a 
lantern 
the english traveler could hardly have predicted the bucolic 
regional capitals rapid industrial growth its rise to prominence 
as the namesake of a doomed democratic republic and its slow decline 
during four decades of communist party rule 
like many small cities in east germany weimar has suffered from 
a chronic shortage of building materials and construction labor 
while the nations communist leaders have invested millions in 
modern concrete housing blocks and launched an ambitious building 
and restoration program in east berlin rural and regional capitals 
have withered and decayed 
despite piecemeal renovation efforts the citys landmarks 
including the stunning 18th century residential palace stand 
peeling and chipped their facades blackened by layers of diesel 
exhaust and coal soot 
outside the city center rickety scaffolding stands in front of 
dozens of onceelegant turnofthecentury apartment buildings 
dont let it fool you said an apartment dweller from a dank 
vestibule theyre not remodeling she said the scaffolding went 
up after a woman was struck and killed by a falling chunk of the 
buildings granite facade 
but were still lucky leipzig and dresden are worse 
considering the tremendous destruction wrought during world war 
ii and the enormous reparations east germany paid to the soviets 
great strides have been made in making the nation the most properous 
in the east bloc 
east berlin is a glittering bustling metropolitan center with 
crowded department stores and cafes there is an emerging nightlife 
that is the envy of russian tourists and anyone who has spent the 
night in dresden rostock or weimar 
slowly laborously the east german provinces are catching up 
dresden once known as the valley of the unaware because its 
geography blocked the reception of western television programs has 
since gotten cable tv 
in weimar workers using period plans have begun rebuilding a row 
of houses on market square that were destroyed during the war 
theyre going to have shops and cafes said a clerk at a 
nearby hotel as you can see weimar needs them very badly 
but for the foreseeable future most east germans will continue 
to live in a crumbling dreary world where as goethe once wrote 
from weimar time does not relinquish its rights either over 
human beings or over monuments 
</TEXT>
