<TEXT>
after months of unsuccessful legal and financial 
maneuvering high voltage engineering corp on monday terminated its 
700 million offer to buy milwaukeebased universal foods corp 
clifford press deputy chairman of high voltage blamed 
wisconsins antitakeover law as the primary reason for giving up 
the fight which began in december 1988 
evan zeppos a spokesman for high voltage said the company would 
continue its effort to have the law overturned in the us supreme 
court but he conceded the chances were slim that the court would 
hear the appeal 
wisconsins law passed in 1987 bars an acquiring company from 
merging with a target company or sellings its assets if the original 
takeover was not approved by the target companys board of directors 
in the unlikely event that the law is overturned high voltage 
will reconsider its offer zeppos said 
the boards rejection of our proposals and its refusal even to 
meet with us to discuss any questions they may have had did not 
serve the interests of universals shareholders press said in his 
statement 
after the announcement the price of universal shares in trading 
on the new york stock exchange slid 225 a share to 3250 a 
share before recovering to 3412 
the 9monthlong takeover attempt was especially costly for high 
voltage which fought unsuccessfully in us district court in 
milwaukee and the 7th circuit court of appeals in chicago to 
overturn the antitakeover law 
zeppos declined comment on the costs but guy a osborn 
president and chief executive of universal foods said high voltage 
had spent more than 15 million in financing and legal costs 
osborn declined comment on the costs incurred by universal foods 
but he said he was pleased high voltage based in burlington mass 
finally had relented 
we feel its good news for us at the company and its good news 
for wisconsin he said its good news for business in general 
our plan now is to devote 110 percent of our time to the business 
goals we are committed to 
high voltage began the battle with a 3050pershare tender 
offer to universal shareholders last december later the company 
upped the ante to 35 and then to 38 it later offered 42 per 
share to universals board of directors for a negotiated merger 
universals board rejected each offer and recommended 
shareholders not tender their shares 
the continued legal battle over the validity of the antitakeover 
law apparently frustrated high voltage said richard elam a 
chicagobased investment analyst with blunt ellis amp loewi inc in 
milwaukee 
they got bogged down in the legal system elam said i 
think high voltage either became impatient or decided it cost too 
much 
