<TEXT>
here is a chronology of major developments in the government 
investigation of drexel burnham lambert inc 
nov 14 1986 speculator ivan boesky agrees to pay a 100 
million penalty to settle charges of trading on inside information 
he agrees to cooperate in a probe of drexel its top financier 
michael milken and others 
april 23 1987 boesky pleads guilty to a single charge of 
conspiracy to lie to the securities and exchange commission 
punishable by five years imprisonment and a 250000 fine 
dec 18 1987 boesky is sentenced to a threeyear prison term 
and no fine 
march 24 1988 boesky begins serving sentence at a 
minimumsecurity facility in lompoc calif 
aug 4 1988 a grand jury indicts five partners in the 
investment concern princetonnewport partners and former drexel 
trader bruce newberg over an alleged tax fraud scheme the 
firstever racketeering charges against securities professionals 
defense lawyers call it a blackmail tactic to pressure defendants 
into testifying against milken drexel and others 
sept 7 1988 the sec accuses drexel milken and three other 
employees of violating a wide range of securities laws most in 
connection with boesky 
dec 6 1988 cary maultasch a senior drexel trader accused in 
the sec case and threatened with numerous indictments turns states 
evidence in a pleabargain agreement with the government 
dec 7 1988 princeton newport partners liquidates because of 
what lawyers for its indicted parters call brutal government misuse 
of the racketeering laws to coerce them into cooperating in the 
drexel investigation 
dec 21 1988 reversing earlier assertions of innocence drexel 
agrees to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a record 650 million 
in fines and restitution to settle what became the biggest 
securities fraud probe in history milken continues to assert 
innocence 
jan 25 1989 the government files formal charges against 
drexel publicly detailing for the first time the accusations to 
which it will plead guilty most stem from the firms alleged 
relationship with boesky 
march 10 1989 drexel reportedly agrees to ban milken for life 
from the firm and prevent other employees from talking business with 
him under a proposed settlement with the sec 
march 22 1989 drexel trader lisa jones is convicted of lying 
to a grand jury the first perjury conviction in the drexel case 
march 29 1989 a grand jury indicts milken brother lowell 
milken and former drexel trader bruce newberg on 98 counts of 
racketeering and fraud potential penalties and fines could exceed 
12 billion plus long prison terms 
april 7 1989 the milkens plead innocent 
april 13 1989 drexel settles civil fraud case with the sec 
under terms that subject the firm to unprecedented federal 
monitoring for three years and force it to sever ties with michael 
milken 
april 25 1980 newberg pleads innocent 
april 26 1989 a judge rejects boeskys petition for early 
release from prison 
june 15 1989 michael milken resigns after 19 years at drexel 
to form his own consulting firm called international capital access 
group lowell milken quits to return to practicing law 
july 31 1989 princetonnewport defendants are found guilty 
signaling that juries are capable of understanding complicated 
securitiesfraud allegations and are willing to convict under the 
punitive racketeering laws 
aug 23 1989 jones is sentenced to 18 months in prison and 
ordered to pay more than 50000 in fines and prison costs 
aug 30 1989 drexel announces several highlevel management 
changes including the appointment of a new president designed to 
strengthen what the firm calls its competitive position 
aug 31 1989 the washington post discloses a confidential sec 
memo detailing what the agency claims was a secret july 1986 meeting 
between boesky and milken aimed at concealing a 53 million payment 
that is believed to be the heart of the governments case against 
milken 
sept 7 1989 after months of challenges and legal delays 
drexel and federal prosecutors reach a final agreement on the guilty 
plea the breakthrough comes after the government drops a demand 
that drexel withhold milkens 1988 compensation of more than 100 
million 
sept 11 1989 drexel pleads guilty to six felonies and begins 
the payment of more than 650 million as punishment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

